<br>
Honour and truth were not always his, hard fought and desparately won were they, this is a story of Tassius, one of many, not the least by far, nor neither the greatest.<br>
<br>
Mark this man, he is to be great!<br>
<br>
Squire of Life:<br>
Young was he, and proud. Not long in the service of the healers in Qeynos. Broad of shoulder and trusting of heart. noble of brow and oft bringer of sigh to the maidens.<br>
<br>
Darkness holds fasination to those of truth, the macabre a lure to their aura. Where more dark or more Macabre than the ancient ruins in the hills of Qeynos? Where would one so of the light be drawn in curiosity? Where would one so bound to the forces of good go to test his arm?<br>
<br>
Which man hears his death knell? better - which man is wise enough to know it as such? Not I, nor ever I.<br>
<br>
It was here we met Tassius and I, more so it was here that Tassius met I, for it was months before I would meet him. <br>
<br>
Wild and unkempt was I, short in tooth, and short of skill. Great of daring, and great of abandon was I though, and never so much than in the chase for the despised Gnoll of BlackBurrow, offspring of my parents murderers.<br>
<br>
It was into the ruins that I ran my prey, short sword in hand, tripped did he on some unseen root, and at my feet did he lye, awaiting the Angel of death to descend. <br>
<br>
Collecting the scalp was I when I noticed the stench, the foulness in the air, the land shuddering under my feet in revulsion. Oh so late was I, too young and too hurt from my hunt to even cry out. The Skeleton laughed, clacking decaying jaws together, raising dessicated arms wide as if to embrace me. <br>
<br>
I hacked desperately at the gruesome visage, time and time again it blocked my swings. Fear I felt, unholy fear, a fear that unmanned me, drove me to my knees. No honour for me, no morning for me, the sun will no longer rise in my eyes. My knell for a Gnoll?<br>
<br>
The Prayer was incanted slowly and deeply, a steady chant of conviction and pride, a blinding silver arc of steel, and the cold, cold wind of death descended, too weak was I to care, to cold was I to feel, to scared was I to breathe. Unconscious was I to all but the sound of my Mothers Song, Feel did I not the strong arms that bore me up, that carried me back - for the second time to the mighty trunks of Surefall.<br>
<br>
Mark this man Tassius my friends, he is to be great!<br>
<br>
This is a story of Tassius, Squire of Life - not the least by far, nor neither the greatest. <p>Semdayen<Br>Ranger of the 13th Season<Br>In the Service of Tunare<Br><Br>'I am not lost - this is the scenic route'
